column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

Numbers increased again this week as agents offered 1407 liveweight cattle. The female sell off continues as 519 cows and 340 heifers made up the majority of the offering along with an extremely mixed selection of 500 steers. Score 2, C and D muscle cattle were again over represented as the current seasonal conditions force many to quit light cattle. The usual trade and processor buyers, feeders and restockers again provided steady competition along with a strong feeder order from the North. The better conditioned cattle sold to marginally stronger competition however lighter cattle returned some mixed results with most again easing in price.

Vealer steers sold 10c to 15c dearer as they made from 220c to 361c with vealer heifers mostly firm and fetching 200c to 240c/kg. Yearling steers sold up to 30c/kg dearer as they made from 240c to 345c however the heifer portion lost a similar ammount as they sold from 150c to 293c/kg.

A small selection of manufacturing bullocks sold firm to make from 255c to 340c/kg.
Grown steers gained 10c to 20c/kg to sell from 213c to 351c with grown heifers easing by up to 30c and fetching 220c to 330c/kg. Store buyers pushed light cows up to 20c/kg dearer as beef types sold from 81c to 220c with dairy types fetching 130c to 140c/kg.
Medium weight cows eased 10c to 15c/kg as beef types sold from 151c to 270c with dairy types ranged from 163c to 210c/kg. Heavy beef cows also eased by up to 20c/kg as beef types ranged from 160c to 317c with dairy types fetching 150c to 257c/kg.
Bulls sold from 180c to 280c/kg.

Market reporter: John Traeger.
